1 petition; and
2 (b) Notify the respondent concerning the allegations and contents of the
3 petition and the date and purpose of the hearing.
4 (7) If after the hearing the court finds by clear and convincing evidence that the risk
5 to public health, safety, or welfare as described in subsection (5)(c) of this section
6 exists, the court shall enter an order prohibiting the respondent from purchasing,
7 possessing, receiving, or having in his or her custody or control a firearm.
8 (8) Within twenty-four (24) hours of issuing the order, the court shall forward, by the
9 most expedient means reasonably available, a copy of the order to the appropriate
10 agency designated for entry of orders of protection into the Law Information
11 Network of Kentucky and to the Department of Kentucky State Police.
12 (9) The Department of Kentucky State Police shall immediately make information
13 about the order available to the National Instant Criminal Background Check
14 System for the purpose of firearm purchaser background checks.
15 (10) (a) Any person found in violation of an order entered under this section shall
16 be guilty of a Class A misdemeanor.
17 (b) Any firearm possessed in violation of this section shall be subject to
18 forfeiture and shall be disposed of as provided in KRS 500.090.
19 Section 2. KRS 237.104 is amended to read as follows:
20 (1) No person, unit of government, or governmental organization shall, during a period
21 of disaster or emergency as specified in KRS Chapter 39A or at any other time,
22 have the right to revoke, suspend, limit the use of, or otherwise impair the validity
23 of the right of any person to purchase, transfer, loan, own, possess, carry, or use a
24 firearm, firearm part, ammunition, ammunition component, or any deadly weapon
25 or dangerous instrument.
26 (2) No person, unit of government, or governmental organization shall, during a period
27 of disaster or emergency as specified in KRS Chapter 39A or at any other time,
